<TITLE> UK Aug mortgage approvals weakest since April </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 LONDON, Oct 1 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - British mortgage approvals for house purchase fell in August to their lowest level since April, data showed on Monday, providing further evidence that the property market is losing momentum. The Bank of England said mortgage approvals -- a leading indicator of the strength of the housing market -- fell to 109,000 in August from an unrevised 115,000 in July. This was the lowest reading since April's 108,000 and below the consensus forecast of 110,000. The figures suggest recent interest rate rises and growing affordability pressures are taking their toll on the housing market. The Bank of England has raised rates five times since August 2006, lifting them to a six-year high of 5.75 percent. However, most economists think rates will start to come down in coming months as the economy slows. Mortgage lending also came in slightly weaker than expected in August, rising by 8.457 billion pounds against expectations of a 9.0 billion pound increase. Growth in consumer credit was somewhat stronger than expected, however, although well below levels seen at the end of last year. The BoE left its final reading of broad money supply growth unchanged at 1.2 percent on the month and 13.5 percent on the ye
